# CLI Standards

## Entry Point

`./agent <command>` — single entry, modular commands, fast startup.

---

## Modular Command Architecture

Commands are plugins in `src/cli_commands/`:

```
src/
├── cli.py                       # Router: discovers + registers commands
└── cli_commands/
    ├── __init__.py              # Command registry
    ├── info.py                  # ./agent info
    ├── lint.py                  # ./agent lint
    ├── tests.py                 # ./agent tests
    ├── budget.py                # ./agent budget (future)
    └── ...                      # New commands = new files
```

Each command module exports: `name`, `help`, `setup(subparser)`, `run(args)`.
Adding a command = adding one file. No changes to cli.py.

---

## Output Format

Optimized for LLM parsing AND human readability:

```
[COMMAND] description
KEY: value
KEY: value
---
SECTION
  ITEM: detail
  ITEM: detail
---
RESULT: OK | FAIL | WARN
```

### Rules

- Structured key-value, not prose
- Sections separated by `---`
- Lists indented 2 spaces
- Status always last line: `RESULT: OK|FAIL|WARN`
- No ANSI colors by default (SSH/LLM safe)
- `--json` flag for machine-parseable output (future)

---

## Exit Codes

| Code | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| 0 | Success |
| 1 | Error (runtime) |
| 2 | Usage error (bad args) |

---

## Conventions

- Lazy imports inside command functions
- Errors to stderr: `print(msg, file=sys.stderr)`
- No interactive prompts (headless agent)
- Every subcommand has `help=` in argparse
